      <div class="page-header">        
        <h4>Bio</h4>
        <p>
          I got my PhD in developmental genetics at <a href="https://www.upct.es/genetica/">Marcos Egea's lab</a> (Cartagena, Spain) in 2012. The desire to design, implement and conduct new analytical strategies shifted my interest to computational biology during my PhD training.
        </p>
        <p>
          I switched to cancer epigenomics during my first postdoc at <a href="http://maplab.cat">Miguel Angel Peinado's lab</a> (Barcelona, Spain), where I enjoyed dealing with multiple challenges, including the analysis of the epigenomics and gene expression status of repetitive elements.
        </p>
        <p>
          Currently, I'm a postdoc with <a href="https://robinsonlabuzh.github.io">Mark D. Robinson</a> and <a href="http://www.baubeclab.org">Tuncay Baubec</a> at the University of Zurich.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm passionate about computational biology in all its favours. I enjoy to engage in collaborative research, but also work in a largely independent manner, mainly to develop new tools addressed to experimentalists to browse and analyze biodata.
        </p>

        <p>
          Luckily, I have worked alongside talented, diverse and excellent researchers, including Marcos Egea (lateral thinking), Julia Weiss (efficiency), Miguel A. Peinado (amiability), Fumichiiro Yamamoto (originality), Mark D. Robinson (reliability), Tuncay Baubec (ambition) and Charlotte Soneson (creativity).
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm also very appreciative of the bright students I tutorized in the past, including: Francisco Chen (Univ. Barcelona, by M.A. Peinado), Alberto Sierco (Univ. Barcelona, by M.A. Peinado), Gustavo Rosell (UOC/UB), Lorena Ponce (UOC/UB), Jose Munuera (UOC/UB), Mar Garcia (UOC/UB) and Chaitra Rao (ETH Zurich, by T. Baubec).
        </p>
      </div>

